Just now

--

So recently I picked up Next.js. While testing the waters, I found myself building a login and signup form for a dashboard. Then I thought why not connect this to a real backend? So I built an auth API with NestJS that matched the expected data shape. Simple enough, right? Wrong.
Here’s what actually happened.
CORS Blocked Everything
The moment my Next.js app on port 3000 tried to reach my NestJS server on port 5000, the browser shut it down immediately. CORS:Cross-Origin Resource Sharing is a browser security policy that blocks requests between different origins(your frontend in my case) unless the server explicitly allows them.
The fix was one method in main.ts:
app.enableCors({
//In nestjs you can use configService to get the clientUrl from .envfilepath
origin: process.env.CLIENT_URL,
methods: ['GET', 'POST', 'PUT', 'DELETE', 'PATCH'],
credentials: true,
});But the lesson was deeper: CORS can’t be fixed from the frontend. It has to come from the server. The browser enforces it, the server permits it. And the origin should always come from an environment variable not hardcoded so it works in every environment without touching the code.
The Rate Limiter Blocked Me From My Own API
I added rate limiting to protect the login endpoint from brute force attacks 3 requests per minute. Smart security decision. What I didn’t expect was blocking myself during testing. I kept hitting the endpoint while debugging and suddenly got a 429 Too Many Requests. My own protection locked me out. The lesson: test with fresh credentials and understand the limits you set, because they apply to everyone including you. Rate limiting doesn’t know the difference between an attacker and a developer.
Helmet: Protecting the Headers
After adding rate limiting to the login endpoint, I realized I was only protecting one door. What about the headers? One of the fastest ways to attack an API is through HTTP headers injecting scripts, clickjacking, bypassing content policies. That’s when I added Helmet. One import, one line in main.ts, and suddenly 14 security headers were added to every response automatically.
app.use(helmet());The AtLeastOneOf Problem: UX Meets Validation
Jacob Nielsen’s usability principle says your product should behave like products people already use. Most apps people use daily offer either a password or a PIN to login not both at the same time, but either one. So I built exactly that a toggle between password and PIN on the login form. Simple UX decision. Nightmare validation problem. Every time I tested from the backend, PIN login with an email identifier failed. The backend was receiving an empty password string alongside the PIN because my frontend still had the password field registered even after switching to PIN mode. The DTO expected either password or PIN not an empty password AND a PIN. I had to build a custom class-validator decorator called AtLeastOneOf that enforced exactly one must be present:
export function AtLeastOneOf(...fields: string[]) {
return function (object: object, propertyName: string) {
registerDecorator({
name: 'atLeastOneOf',
target: object.constructor,
propertyName,
validator: {
validate(_: any, args: ValidationArguments) {
return fields.some(
(field) => (args.object as any)[field] !== undefined,
);
},
defaultMessage() {
return `At least one of ${fields.join(', ')} must be provided`;
},
},
});
};
}And on the frontend, I had to unregister the unused field when toggling:
const switchToPin = () => {
unregister('password');
setUsePin(true);
};One UX decision created a full-stack validation challenge I didn’t see coming.
Expected Data vs Actual Data
This was the most expensive lesson of all. What you think you’re sending and what you’re actually sending are often two different things. My backend DTO expected either a password or a PIN. My frontend was sending an empty password string alongside the PIN because React Hook Form still held the registered value even after I switched to PIN mode. The backend saw an empty password, failed validation, and threw a 400 Bad Request. The fix: always check the Network tab payload before debugging the backend. The answer is usually right there you’re just not looking at the right place.
The Takeaway
Connecting a frontend to a backend taught me more about backend engineering than building the backend alone ever did. You don’t truly understand CORS until the browser blocks you. You don’t truly understand rate limiting until it locks you out. You don’t truly understand validation until a UX decision breaks your API. Build the full stack. Break things. The errors are the education.
